<Base title="Philosophy — myalicia">
  <h1>Philosophy</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    myalicia is one possible answer to a design question: what does it
    look like to build software that takes the shape of a single human,
    and grows with them?
  </p>

  <h2>Humorphism, in one paragraph</h2>

  <p>
    <a href="https://humorphism.com">Humorphism</a> is the design philosophy
    that technology should take a shape that fits the human, not the other
    way around. It's the ergonomic principle applied to AI: stop building
    chatbots that everyone has to learn to talk to, start designing
    relationships that learn the person they're with. Where skeuomorphism
    once made digital things look like physical things so we could approach
    them, humorphism makes AI things <em>respond</em> like attentive
    presences so we can be in relationship with them.
  </p>

  <h2>From chatbot to teammate</h2>

  <p>
    Most AI products today are tools you adapt to. You learn the prompt
    that gets the result. You phrase your question in the way the model
    parses cleanly. You contort.
  </p>

  <p>
    A teammate doesn't ask you to contort. A teammate notices how you
    work, picks up your idiom, remembers what you said yesterday, and
    catches the patterns you can't see in yourself. A teammate has
    different conversations with different people, and gets better at
    one relationship over time, not worse.
  </p>

  <p>
    myalicia is what the architecture of that looks like, made buildable.
  </p>

  <h2>Why three loops</h2>

  <p>
    Most agents only have one loop: the conversation. You speak, they
    answer, the moment ends. There's no metabolism — nothing that turns
    today's exchange into tomorrow's understanding.
  </p>

  <p>
    A relationship needs three depths of attention to work:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Listen</strong> — being present in the moment</li>
    <li><strong>Notice</strong> — catching patterns across moments</li>
    <li><strong>Know</strong> — coming to know the person, over time</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Each loop reads from and writes to a shared substrate (your vault,
    your notes, your archetype). Awareness compounds because three
    different cadences of reflection are always running. That compounding
    is what makes a teammate, not a tool.
  </p>

  <h2>What we ask of designers</h2>

  <p>
    The agentic era asks designers to think differently. Stop designing
    interfaces. Start designing relationships. Stop designing chatbots.
    Start designing the metabolic loops by which an AI comes to know
    someone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Concretely: contribute <strong>awareness primitives</strong>. A reading-pattern
    primitive. A calendar-rhythm primitive. A relationship-graph primitive.
    Each one is a small, opinionated module that turns some slice of
    life into structured memory the loops can metabolize. That's the work
    of design now.
  </p>
</Base>
